|Aino
|Means "the only one" in Finnish.
|-
|Anna
|Form of Channah (Hannah) used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
|-
|Anni
|Finnish, Estonian, German and Danish diminutive of Anna.
|-
|Elina
|Finnish, Estonian and Swedish form of Helen.
|-
|Elli
|Diminutive of names beginning with El, such as Elizabeth.
|-
|Emma
|Originally a short form of Germanic names that began with the element ermen meaning "whole" or "universal".
|-
|Essi
|Finnish diminutive of Esther.
|-
|Hanna
|Form of Channah (Hannah) in several languages.
|-
|Heidi
|German diminutive of Adelheid.
|-
|Henna
|Finnish feminine form of Heinrich (Henry).
|-
|Ida
|Derived from the Germanic element id meaning "work, labour".
|-
|Inka
|Frisian and Finnish feminine form of Inge, and a German variant.
|-
|Jasmin
|German and Finnish form of Jasmine, as well as an English variant.
|-
|Jenni
|Finnish form of Jenny, and an English variant.
|-
|Johanna
|Latinate form of Greek Ioanna (Joanna).
|-
|Julia
|Feminine form of the Roman family name Julius.
|-
|Krista
|Short form of Kristina.
|-
|Maria
|Latin form of Greek Μαρία, from Hebrew מִרְיָם (Mary).
|-
|Milla
|Short form of Camilla and other names that end in milla.
|-
|Nina
|Short form of names that end in nina, such as Antonina or Giannina.
|-
|Oona
|Irish variant and Finnish form of Úna.
|-
|Pinja
|Means "stone pine" in Finnish.
|-
|Roosa
|Finnish form of Rosa. It also means "pink" in Finnish.
|-
|Salla
|A variant of Salli. Salla is also the name of both a fell and a municipality in Lapland, Finland.
|-
|Sanna
|Short form of Susanna. It can also be derived from Swedish sann meaning "true".
|-
|Sofia
|Form of Sophia used in various languages.
|-
|Suvi
|Means "summer" in Finnish.
|-
|Tiia
|Finnish and Estonian short form of Dorothea.
|-
|Vilma
|Form of Wilma in several languages.
|-
|Wilma
|Short form of Wilhelmina.
